<dl id="n42087b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n42" href="#n42087b">N42 (VI.B.31)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n42all.htm#n42087b"> 87(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> zdrastvitya / = zdrast = be / healthy <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n42087b"><li>FW 91.36 </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/lexd.htm#n42087b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/l39d.htm#n42087b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n42087b">MS BL 47475-38v</ms> </li><li>JJA 46:185 <a name="dd8" href="../../FF/fdra/dda.htm#dd8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/d/dd8.htm#n42087b">Draft: I.4&sect;1.8</a>/2.8</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><mark><b>Zdr&acute;stvitye!</b> &mdash; Contracted very often into &ldquo;Zdrast!&rdquo;</mark> The Russian form of greeting meaning &ldquo;<mark>Be healthy</mark>!&rdquo; Adopted by the troops it bacame the general form of greeting among themselves. <small> Basil Hargrave, <a name="BHOM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BHOM"><cite title="source">Origins and Meanings of Popular Phrases &amp; Names Including Those Which Came Into Use During The Great War</cite></a> (?Apr 1932) 376</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
